div.p:
One of the Catlings was bitten in the Cartilagineous part of the Ear, without any appearance
of blood at the place of the biting; and it ecaped. The other, which was much les, and a very noted one by the blacknes of its colour and by having her ears cut off, was purpoely wounded on the upper part of her neck behind, and alo at the lower bone of the hinder part of the head; its skin alowas eparated from the fleh round about the wound, and on both ides, almot as far as to the fore part of the neck: And then as much of the yellow liquor as they would was put into both ides as well as into the wound. This Cat held down her head, by reaon doubtles of the pain he endured by having in a manner been flead alive; feeling alo ome pain in two other places, where he had been wounded and flead. Some of the by-tanders began already to mutter, and aid, I hould be cat, and the Cat would certainly dye; yet notwithtanding the Cat did not dye, though he was very little and taken out from under her dam; and he was hew'd to the company 24 hours after, ound and afe, although he had neither uck'd nor eaten any thing all that time. And 'tis remarkable enough, that this very Cat, having been returned to a Fryar to whom he belonged, and being grown big, hath yet to this day the hind-part of her skull uncloed at the place of her wound;
and notwithtanding all that, & the falling off of ome fleh and skin, that were ever'd from the places where he was flead, he is very lively and full of play, and very divertiing mimick getures.
